File: A soccer ball seen next to a net. AFP/Roberto Schmidt JOHANNESBURG - After much speculation and following an emergency committee meeting of the Confederation of African Football, a decision has been made to postpone the CAF qualifiers for the 2022 FIFA World Cup. They were due to be played next month, but CAF says current challenges caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, as well as the need to ensure the best playing conditions, have forced the postponement. The games will now take place between September 2021 and March 2022. READ: Hugo Broos appointed new Bafana Bafana coach The guardian of African football said in a statement that it is now working on reassessing its COVID-19 protocols and processes. South Africa were scheduled to play Zimbabwe next month. The postponement gives newly-appointed Bafana Bafana coach Hugo Broos more time to put together the best squad for the qualifiers.